 class=m><span class=title> Background history...</span><hr size=1> This is sort of an introduction I put together to explain the background behind my manga script to put it up on my webpage (I redid the original story plot intro on my old webpage.) I think this is alot more in depth, and It explains alot more about the manga... I'd like someone to proofread because I'm a typo freak and I always overlook something even when I check over it a thousand tiems. I'd also like to hear what you think about it as well. (Yes... It is quite kenshin-clad.)<br>
<br>
&quot;The year was 1864, and Japan had become a breeding ground for resistance groups and corrupt governemt officials. Many years before this date arrived on the shores of Japan the black ships from the west lead by Commander Perry. The black steam ships frightened Japan and some citizens began to doubt the strength of thier own millitary, and the courage of the Shogunate.<br>
Many clans and factions were displeased at how the Shogunate had cowered before the black ships and thus, the beggining of a great rebellion began.<br>
This rebellion was known as thre Bakumatsu, or &quot;Twilight of the Bakufu.&quot; The main contenders were the Ishin rebellion, and the Shogunate. The Ishin Shishi were a loose group of civillians that had only one goal called &quot;Sonno Joi,&quot; which means &quot;Revere the Emperor. Expel the barbarians.&quot;<br>
This group of rebels contained many factions that did not agree with each other's actions such as the conflicts between Choshu and Satsuma. <br>
The Tokugawa Shogunate at that time became angry at the rebellion taking place and enlisted his own army to deal with the rebels. The Shogunate gathered his personal military known as the Bakufu, and a group of swordsmen from Mibu, later to be called the Shinsengumi, to fight alongside him.<br>
<br>
There was also a war within this rebellion that pit two factions against eachother. One of these factions were Ishin Shishi, and the other Bakufu. The Koutsu Ishin fought valiantly against the Hokuten samurai and eventually defeated them on the night of June 5, 1864. That was the same night that the Ikedaya incident occured, where the Shinsengumi halted an attempt by Choshu extremists who were planning on burning Kyoto to the ground and assassinate key members of the Bakufu in the chaos of the flames. During this night, the Hokuten fell into despair and were never heard from again.<br>
<br>
Many years have passed and the Ishin Shishi won the rebellion and the Shogunate calmly admitted defeat, yet planned his next assault and soon declared the &quot;Meiji&quot; restoration illegal. This was known as the Boshin wars, or the &quot;Bakumatsu no Doran,&quot; which was the &quot;Bakumatsu's end.&quot;<br>
The fallen prince of the Hokuten clan did not stop defending his country the night his father's clan fell, and so Hokuten Jinshira fought the Boshin wars as a member of the Bakufu. Sadly for Jinshira, the Bakufu lost against the new Meiji Ishin who were equipped with young, resilliant soldiers and arsenal that would bring a god to his knees. And so the Meiji restoration had begun...<br>
The Hokuten prince managed to return to his home town of Otsu, but he wasn't finished yet... There was a score left unsettled the night his clan met thier fate, and he was not about to let his family's name be tarnished any longer.<br>
<br>
Peace has been restored to Japan through the brave efforts of the Ishin Shishi, yet who is to say who were evil and who were righteaous.<br>
<br>
Meiji, year five... Our story begins.&quot;<br>
